'''Kazama Shrine''' (かざまじんじゃ) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in the Kazama area of {{ill|Nagano City|ja|長野市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Nagano Prefecture.

The shrine is identified as a {{ill|Shikinai-sha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== Overview ==
The shrine is situated approximately 3 km southeast of {{ill|Nagano Station|ja|長野駅|12=draft|12=draft}}, in a residential area slightly off the prefectural road {{ill|Nagano Prefectural Road 34|ja|長野県道34号長野菅平線|12=draft|12=draft}}.

Records indicate that in {{ill|860 CE|ja|貞観2nd year|12=draft|12=draft}}, "Hyoubetsu Shrine" was granted Rank in the court hierarchy. In {{ill|979 CE|ja|天元2nd year|12=draft|12=draft}}, Tadanobu Yajima, a minor branch of the {{ill|Suwa clan|ja|諏訪氏|1=Suwa clan|12=draft|12=draft}}, was dispatched as a steward and took the surname Kazama, marking the origins of various {{ill|Kazama clans|ja|風間氏|12=draft|12=draft}}.

The shrine preserves a traditional lion dance known as the "Kazama Shrine Daidaikagura Lion Dance," which has been performed since {{ill|1822 CE|ja|文政5th year|12=draft|12=draft}}. The dance features male lions wielding swords and no lyrics. It was designated a {{ill|Nagano City Selected Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|長野市選択無形民俗文化財|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|1998 CE|ja|平成10th year|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>[http://bunkazai-nagano.jp/modules/dbsearch/page1166.html Kazama Shrine Daidaikagura Lion Dance] - Nagano City Cultural Heritage Database</ref>

== History ==
* {{ill|596 CE|ja|推古天皇5th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (August): Mentioned in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}.
* {{ill|860 CE|ja|貞観2nd year|12=draft|12=draft}} (February): Recorded in the {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|12=draft|12=draft}}.
* {{ill|979 CE|ja|天元2nd year|12=draft|12=draft}}: Tadanobu Yajima of the Suwa clan was dispatched as a steward and adopted the name Kazama.
* {{ill|1697 CE|ja|元禄10th year|12=draft|12=draft}}: Renamed from Suwa Shrine to Kazama Daimyōjin.<ref>[http://weekly-nagano.main.jp/2012/01/127.html 127 Kazama Shrine: The Wind deity Renamed as a Shikinai-sha] - Weekly Nagano</ref>
* {{ill|1822 CE|ja|文政5th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (September): Renamed Kazama Shrine by the Yoshida clan, who served as shrine administrators.
* {{ill|1998 CE|ja|平成10th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (August 1): The Kazama Shrine Daidaikagura Lion Dance was designated as a Nagano City Selected Intangible Folk Cultural Property.

== Access ==
* From {{ill|Nagano Station|ja|長野駅|12=draft|12=draft}} (JR East and Nagano Electric Railway), take the Alpico Kōtsū (Kawanakajima Bus) Route 46 to the "Kazama" stop. The shrine is a 2-minute walk from the bus stop.

== Nearby Facilities ==
* Nishikazama Community Center
* Nagano City Office Dainoshima Branch
* Nagano City Dainoshima Elementary School

